article.headline: Carter scores 22 points for Lady Techsters
article.linkText: La Tech beats UTEP, gets 13th straight win
article.story:
EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- Thirteen was a lucky number for
Louisiana Tech on Thursday night.

Amisha Carter scored 22 points to lead the Lady Techsters (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) to
their 13th straight win, an 83-60 victory over UTEP.

"I'm very proud about what we did tonight," coach Kurt Budke
said. "We did a good job of holding them to one shot and
controlling the lane inside."

The win kept Louisiana Tech (21-2, 14-1 Western Athletic) tied
with Rice for the conference lead.

The Techsters led 10-6 with 11:28 left in the first half and
took control of the game by going on a 22-3 run to increase their
edge to 32-9 with 5:25 remaining.

UTEP (14-11, 9-7) cut Louisiana Tech's lead to 49-38 with 14
minutes left in the game. The Lady Techsters responded with a 20-7
run over the next five minutes to retake the momentum and push the
lead to 69-45 with 8:52 left.

"It's all about effort," Budke explained. "I thought we lost
our intensity a little at the start of the second half but we got
it together and took back control."

Carter agreed.

"We played pretty well tonight but we could have done better in
the second half," she said. "Even though they cut the lead a
little bit, I felt we had the game all the way."

Trina Frierson and Erica Smith-Taylor scored 14 points apiece
for Louisiana Tech. Lakiste Barkus added 13.

Louisiana Tech's defense held the Miners to just 34-percent
shooting and had nine steals on the way to forcing 20 turnovers.

"We were real up and down tonight," UTEP coach Keitha Green
said. "They're the type of team that is so talented you've got to
play your 'A' game to have a chance, and we didn't do that."

Ingrid Goslin led UTEP with 16 points. Vaida Zagurskyte scored
14 points and Jonna Launiainen added 11.

Louisiana Tech punished UTEP in the paint, outscoring the Miners
32-12.
